Local test:
# Start the local server with:
bundle exec jekyll serve
# Open your web browser
http://localhost:4000/ 

Jekyll-based GitHub pages structure:
├── _config.yml           ← your main settings file
├── _data/
│   ├── about-me.yml      ← “About Me” data
│   ├── experience.yml    ← your experience entries
│   ├── skills.yml        ← your skills list
│   └── publication.yml   ← your publications markdown blob
├── _includes/
│   └── header.html       ← shared partials (optional)
├── _layouts/
│   ├── default.html      ← your base layout (includes CSS/Font-Awesome links)
│   └── page.html         ← other custom layouts
├── assets/
│   ├── css/
│   │   └── style.css     ← your main stylesheet
│   └── plugins/
│       └── font-awesome/
│           ├── css/
│           │   └── all.min.css
│           └── webfonts/
│               └── ⋯
├── index.md              ← your homepage (pulls in data via `site.data`)
├── resume.html           ← a standalone page
├── publications.html     ← optional standalone page
├── contact.html          ← optional standalone page
└── publication.md        ← if you still have a root-level include for publications

Key points

_config.yml lives at the root and defines your baseurl, site-wide variables (profile, social links, etc.).

_data/ holds structured YAML files (about-me.yml, experience.yml, skills.yml, publication.yml) that you pull into your templates with site.data.*.

_includes/ (or you can use include_relative) is where you put any small reusable snippets or raw Markdown that you want to inject.

_layouts/ defines your page shell(s). default.html typically contains your <head> (with CSS + Font Awesome), sidebar, and {{ content }} injection.

assets/ is where you keep all your CSS, JS, images, and (in your case) a local copy of Font Awesome (both the css/ and webfonts/ folders).

Top-level .md/.html files become site pages—index.md for the homepage (where you loop through your _data sets), plus any other pages you need (resume.html, contact.html, etc.).
